If you don't make the distinction I'm drawing between rights and goods, you will end up defining all desirable things as rights, without defining who is obligated to provide them, and why.
Again, you're missing my distinction between a social good essential to ensuring a non-contingent right, and what is essentially a claim on contingent resources.
It certainly could, and has, throughout history.
My "right" to life is a restraint on others not to kill me, not a claim on others to prevent me from catching ... I dunno, the flu ... and ceasing to live.

Now you will proceed to argue that provision of health care as a social good is intertwined with the right to life. But really, what we have is a liberty to life, a restraint on others that our lives not be taken away, not a positive claim on others to remain alive.

I think there is an argument that the provision of specific social goods is intertwined with a non-contingent right. But that is different from asserting a right that is simply a claim on resources, and nothing more.

The question is whether the unwillingness to provide what is essentially a good (DNA testing) impinges on legal fairness (which is a right) or not. It only becomes so if the state has the resources to deploy such evidence.
No, not necessarily. It is good and desirable if it can. But due process can exist around a campfire, if need be.
An accused person, in any society, has an absolute claim that truth be the object of justice. It is not contingent on any technology, resource, or skill.
No, due process is a claim to fair behavior, which is not finite, not to private or social resources, which may or may not exist.

What standard of health care is a person entitled to? Yesterday that standard did not exist, tomorrow it will seem woefully inadequate. You set yourself up for a moving and meaningless target, contingent on what can be produced.
But until the 20th Century, this was largely meaningless. You could not claim effective medical care, because what we mean by that now simply did not exist.

Technology and the complexity of legal systems may change what due process means, and what it requires, but every society has the means, within itself, to pursue criminal justice to the best of its ability.
No, every society, no matter how primitive, can deliver due process (fair treatment and hearing of the accused, to ascertain the truth and apply justice fairly), though the means may differ.
The relevance of this becomes clearer when we look beyond the present and examine the past, when very few societies indeed had the means to deliver this good.

There are societies that simply cannot provide childhood education - either labor, skills, or resources are too scarce. They are not denying a right, they are simply unable to deliver a desirable good.
I would call childhood education a good. Public defenders is a good, but it's closely tied to the notion of due process, which is a right.
I'd put it somewhat differently: a right cannot be contingent on something that must be produced before it can be claimed.
You can pass a law saying an orange is a vegetable. Doesn't mean I can't dispute that it's not actually a vegetable.
And for all the Europeans, Canadians, Australians who are going to say "it's a right in our country", I'm not talking about positive law, I'm talking about basic principles and definitions.

Health care is neither a right nor a privilege, it's a good. It's a complex good that displays aspects of both a private good and a public good. https:// twitter.com/DCampoamor/sta tus/965772775326613504 …
